71	Belleisle Golf Club	belleisle-golf-club	#Belleisle Golf Club\r\n\r\nBelleisle golf course, in the main town of Ayr, is far from a course of modest aspiration. James Braid designed the course in 1927, to satisfy an increasingly insatiable demand for the game.\r\n\r\nIt is rather a course of genuine and proven quality, providing an enjoyable challenge to hordes of appreciative golfers who are only too happy to sing its many praises.\r\n\r\nBelleisle would probably be the best public course in Scotland if it weren`t for those upstarts, St Andrews and Carnoustie. Tour players like to sharpen their pencils before major competitions here! That’s how good it is, and surely one of the few true municipals to host professional tournaments.\r\n\r\nBelleisle is a classic parkland course of genuine character. Set in the harmonious woodland of Belleisle Park, its beech tree lined and extra long fairways are interlaced by the serpentine like Curtecan Burn.\r\n\r\nThere are only two par fours under 400 yards and a cracker of a par three at the 17th. If for some reason you don’t manage Turnberry or Royal Troon, don’t miss this!	2011-08-31 15:27:28.65574	2011-09-09 16:05:12.372292	courses	55.663644,-3.617249	9	Scotland	Golf at Belleisle Golf Club, Ayr, Scotland | Your Golf Tours	Belleisle golf course, in the main town of Ayr, is far from a course of modest aspiration. James Braid designed the course in 1927, to satisfy an increasingly insatiable demand for the game.
3	Highlands and Royal Aberdeen	highlands-and-royal-aberdeen	# Highlands and Royal Aberdeen\r\n\r\nThe Highlands and Aberdeen Golf Tour will enable you to see and visit some of the most naturally beautiful places in the world as well as some of Scotland’s very best golf courses. Many of the golfing gems in the Highlands are unheralded when compared with Scotland’s more famous creations like Turnberry, St Andrews and Carnoustie yet the quality of golf on offer in this region is second to none. \r\n\r\nYour tour will see you visit a multitude of stunning links courses, some of which hold historic significance such as Royal Aberdeen and Royal Dornoch and some of which represent the new breed of stunning links golf on offer in Scotland including Castle Stuart, which recently held the Scottish Open as the prelude to the Open Championship on the European Tour. With a host of championship venues on offer it is easy to see why so many travelling golfers select this fine region for their golf tour each year.\r\n\r\nAlthough the likes of Dornoch, Nairn and Cruden Bay will be popular for those wanting a true links experience there are also some superb inland courses to enjoy such as Spey Valley which sweeps through fields of established heather and Boat of Garten which is revered as one of James Braid’s finest creations. With so many different golf courses available to enjoy, this tour can be customised to create a truly unique Scottish golf experience.	2011-08-30 15:25:23.143309	2011-09-13 09:20:07.014795	tours	57.604221,-1.977539	8	Scotland	Highlands & Royal Aberdeen Golf Tours – Castle Stuart|Your Golf Tours	\N
52	Brora Golf Club	brora-golf-club	#Brora Golf Club\r\n\r\nThe golf club in Brora was established in 1891.\r\n\r\nIn 1923 James Braid, five times Open champion and prolific designer of golf courses, the most famous of which is Gleneagles, visited the course and redesigned the 18-hole layout which has stood the passing of time and remains a fair and challenging test of a true traditional links course.\r\n\r\nAs with all seaside links there are some very special places throughout this course; the panorama of seascape and landscape from the second tee, the proximity of the sea to the 9th green and the beauty of the 13th green, one of the jewels in Braids crown. Tarbatness, the 17th, so called because of the lighthouse which gives you the line and with the elevated tee, is one of the best driving holes in all of Scotland.\r\n\r\nBrora golf course represents all the attributes of a traditional Scottish Highland links, with a classic layout, an easy opening hole, and a short hole facing each cardinal point of the compass, you will have to adapt and manufacture according to whither the course is running fast or slow.\r\n\r\nOverall the golf course is a real treat, the clubhouse is modern and comfortable, the catering is excellent. But perhaps the over-riding, all important, feature is the atmosphere warm, friendly & welcoming.	2011-08-31 15:06:55.090519	2011-09-09 16:36:49.167726	courses	57.189855,-1.395264	7	Scotland	Golf at Brora Golf Club, Scotland | Your Golf Tours	Brora golf course represents all the attributes of a traditional Scottish Highland links, with a classic layout, an easy opening hole, and a short hole facing each cardinal point of the compass, you will have to adapt and manufacture according to whither the course is running fast or slow.
135	Carnoustie	carnoustie	#Carnoustie\r\n\r\nOn the east coast of Scotland, not far from St Andrews lies Carnoustie. Carnoustie Golf Links has had 2 Open Championships in the last 10 years (1999 and 2007) which has reignited much deserved interest in the Carnoustie Championship course.\r\n\r\nAll will remember Jean van de Velde’s inauspicious demise in 1999 and on a happier note Padraig Harrington’s first major win came in 2007 when he defeated Sergio Garcia in a play-off. Ben Hogan has been remembered here as the 1953 Open Champion. The 6th hole is now called Hogan’s Alley, referring to the tight line he took between the bunkers and the out of bounds on each of the 4 days play.\r\n\r\nThere are other great local Scottish golf courses in the surrounding area, namely Monifieth, Downfield and Panmure which are all great examples of golf in Scotland. Although not very well known they have all been used over the years as Open qualifying venues.\r\n\r\nThe Carnoustie area is only 30 minutes from St Andrews, 1hr 30 mins from Edinburgh and 2 hrs from Glasgow. Our featured hotel in the area is the Carnoustie Hotel which stands directly behind the 18th green of the Championship course.	2011-09-01 16:44:41.451186	2011-09-06 15:38:38.174765	regions		\N	Scotland	Golf in Carnoustie | Your Golf Tours	\N
