94	Portmarnock	portmarnock	#Portmarnock\r\n\r\nA revered name in golf both in Ireland and worldwide, Portmarnock is a course to aspire to play, and for lovers of traditional links, it is up there with the best. Located on the Howth Peninsula, the club enjoys a glorious isolation where the only thing to do is play golf.\r\n\r\nThe golf course at Portmarnock Golf Club, not to be confused with the Portmarnock Links Resort, is routed through the splendid sand dunes of the coastal fringes, and the character of the land is the driving force behind the nature of the holes. Like all good seaside courses, working with the land and the elements is the only way to negotiate safe passage.\r\n\r\nThe traditional clubhouse looks out over the golf course, where you will be completely exposed to the wind; Portmarnock is a stern but fair test, and is a links experience of the old fashioned variety that can only be enjoyed at select venues in the UK and Ireland. Your golf tour in Dublin will be all the more memorable with a round here.	2011-08-31 16:08:11.540475	2011-09-08 15:44:53.368874	courses		\N	Ireland	Golf at Portmarnock, Ireland | Your Golf Tours	A revered name in golf both in Ireland and worldwide, Portmarnock is a course to aspire to play, and for lovers of traditional links, it is up there with the best. Located on the Howth Peninsula, the club enjoys a glorious isolation where the only thing to do is play golf.
24	Prestwick Golf Club	prestwick-golf-club	#Prestwick Golf Club\r\n\r\nPrestwick Golf Club is situated just half an hour south west of Glasgow on the famous golfing Ayrshire coast.\r\n\r\nA stretch of land unequalled anywhere in the world for prime golfing terrain. Prestwick shares it boundaries with Royal Troon and is just 20 minutes from Turnberry, with Open final qualifying courses such as Kilmarnock Barassie, Glasgow Gailes, Western Gailes and Irvine Bogside all within just 5 minutes drive.\r\n\r\nThe first Open championship was held at Prestwick in 1860 and was organised by the members who subscribed £25 to purchase the red morocco belt with silver clasps. It was won by Willie Park of Musselburgh with a score of 174 over 36 holes. The belt was won in three successive years by Young Tom Morris from 1868 to 1870 and thus became his property. When Morris won for the third time, in 1870, he had a first round score of 47 (over 12 holes) was has never been equalled or bettered. He started with a three at the 578yard first hole that in those days was probably a par 6. His Belt is now in the keeping of the Royal and Ancient Golf Club of St.Andrews. A replica belt was presented to Sandy Lyle, the winner of the 125th Anniversary Open Championship at Royal St.Georges Golf Club in 1985, another is on display in the Cardinal room in the Prestwick clubhouse.\r\n\r\nThere was no Championship in1871, and thereafter Prestwick, the Royal and Ancient Golf Club of St.Andrews, and the Honourable Company of Edinburgh joined forces to purchase the current Claret Jug, played for in the Open Championship for £30. When the Championship was revived in 1872 Young Tom won again, thus winning the Open Four times in a row. A feat no other Golfer has ever matched, or likely will. In 1914 Harry Vardon won the Open for a record sixth time, three victories of which were won at Prestwick.\r\n\r\nA stone cairn to the west of the Clubhouse, marks the first tee of the original 12 hole course, from which the first Open was played. The 1st hole measured 578 yards to what is now the 16th green, where in 1870 Tom Morris Jr holed out in three strokes using hickory shafts and a gutty golf ball. Seven of the original greens are still played on today.	2011-08-31 14:08:06.502268	2011-09-08 15:45:59.570606	courses		\N	Scotland	Golf at Prestwick Golf Club, Scotland | Your Golf Tours	Prestwick Golf Club is situated just half an hour south west of Glasgow on the famous golfing Ayrshire coast, a stretch of land unequalled anywhere in the world for prime golfing terrain.
127	Quinta do Lago 	quinta-do-lago	#Quinta do Lago \r\n\r\nThere are few golf resorts that can rival Quinta do Lago in terms of an illustrious reputation, beautiful natural surroundings and an abundance of top quality golf. With three outstanding courses in the Algarve's most sought after postcode, Quinta do Lago should be high on your wish list for a golf tour in Portugal.\r\n\r\nHaving hosted many prestigous events including the national Open on the European tour, Quinta do Lago has a rich tradition. With the recent opening of its third championship layout, the resort has never been better placed to satisfy the needs of hungry golfers worldwide.\r\n\r\nArguably the grand old lady of Quinta do Lago, the South Course is often the favourite of the golfing purist; in fact, the layout is frequently compared favourably with Augusta National, with the same sweeping fairways sculpted through avenues of mature pines and beautifully crafted trees. The South is the closest of the courses to the shoreline, and is a safe bet for a top day's golf.\r\n\r\nThe North Course was opened in the year 2000, and has been extremely well received. The style is similar to the South, but it is more than 500 yards shorter, so does not present such a stern test. Most recently, Quinta do Lago introduced the world to the Laranjal, its third course; the Laranjal is a genuine championship layout, modern in style and has made waves in its early days.	2011-08-31 16:42:42.477835	2011-09-08 15:46:33.730175	courses		\N	Portugal	Golf at Quinta Do Lago, Portugal | Your Golf Tours	With three outstanding courses in the Algarve's most sought after postcode, Quinta do Lago should be high on your wish list for a golf tour in Portugal.\r\n
115	Roman Road Course, Celtic Manor	roman-road-course-celtic-manor	#Roman Road Course, Celtic Manor\r\n\r\nThe Roman Road Course was the first to be unveiled at The Celtic Manor Resort, and is a former host to the Wales Open (2005 & 2006). Since its 1995 inception, considerable investment has been undertakent to improve the Roman Road's conditioning and playability, and the result is a fantastic and scenic resort layout.\r\n\r\nDesigner Robert Trent Jones Jnr had a lovely parcel of rolling Welsh land on which to fashion the Roman Road, but he had to literally plan around the Roman roads that were uncovered during construction. His layout, despite the name, has far more twists than a Roman highway, with plenty of intrigue facing visiting golfers.\r\n\r\nThe Roman Road winds around the Resort Hotel at The Celtic Manor, and remains a very popular option for golfing groups enjoying Wales' leading resort. Although it may not have the knock-out drama and stadium toughness of the neighbouring Twenty Ten Course, The Roman Road is s solid test, and was at the time of its opening ranked as Wales' leading inland course.	2011-08-31 16:31:43.92018	2011-09-08 15:47:38.373316	courses		\N	Wales	Golf at Celtic Manor, Roman Road | Your Golf Tours	The Roman Road Course was the first to be unveiled at The Celtic Manor Resort, and is a former host to the Wales Open. Since its 1995 inception, considerable investment has been undertakent to improve the Roman Road's conditioning and playability, and the result is a fantastic and scenic resort layout.
98	Royal County Down	royal-county-down	#Royal County Down\r\n\r\nMany of the best respected golf course rankings place Royal County Down in second place behind New Jersey's shrouded-in-mystery Pine Valley, making it arguably the best links course in the world; enough said really - an essential experience for any lover of seaside golf.\r\n\r\nThe iconic Championship Course at County Down is set against the backdrop of the majestic Mountains of Mourne, with views also of the sea. Most recently on the world stage for the 2007 Walker Cup, County Down is a relentless test of seaside golf, and a stern examination for every visitor.\r\n\r\nOld Tom Morris, the legend forever entwined with St Andrews, designed the Championship Course as part of an excursion to the Emerald Isle, and it may be his greatest legacy outside the home of golf.	2011-08-31 16:10:19.892332	2011-09-08 15:48:12.488764	courses		\N	Ireland	Golf at Royal County Down, Northern Ireland | Your Golf Tours	Many of the best respected golf course rankings place Royal County Down in second place behind New Jersey's shrouded-in-mystery Pine Valley, making it arguably the best links course in the world; enough said really - an essential experience for any lover of seaside golf.
125	Vale do Lobo	vale-do-lobo	#Vale do Lobo\r\n\r\nVale do Lobo is one of the most celebrated names in golf on the Algarve and indeed anywhere in Portugal. The prestigious residential estate, also home to the Dona Filipa Hotel, stretches down to the stunning sandy beaches, and also has two glorious golf courses.\r\n\r\nThe Ocean and Royal Courses at Vale do Lobo wind through the mature avenues of trees and past luxury villas, providing glorious views and a lovely golfing experience. The two courses are hard to separate in terms of their quality, but the Royal is arguably the more established and more challenging.\r\n\r\nTaking on the Royal Course, you will sweep inland and through some tight driving holes before the route meanders towards the coast; the 15th is played directly out towards the sea before the iconic 16th, a long par-3 across the cliffs with the beach alongside, provides the famous Vale do Lobo photo opportunity.\r\n\r\nThe 16th is a demanding hole, and many fail to negotiate it with the beach a constant threat, but the experience of this famous hole encapsulates the essence of the beautiful Vale do Lobo. 	2011-08-31 16:41:46.108247	2011-09-08 15:54:30.188126	courses		\N	Portugal	Golf at Vale do Lobo, Algarve, Portugal | Your Golf Tours	Vale do Lobo is one of the most celebrated names in golf on the Algarve and indeed anywhere in Portugal. The prestigious residential estate, also home to the Dona Filipa Hotel, stretches down to the stunning sandy beaches, and also has two glorious golf courses.
45	Royal Dornoch	royal-dornoch	#Royal Dornoch\r\n\r\nIn 2002 the Club celebrated 125 years since its foundation, but that understates the history of Royal Dornoch by at least a long drive with a jumbo driver.\r\n\r\nCenturies before a golf club was formed at Dornoch, the game of golf was recorded as being played in 1616 on the town lands on the links along the seashore. The Club is proud to play on the third of the first three golf links in Scotland following St Andrews 1552 and Leith 1593.\r\n\r\nA number of prestigious golf architects have contributed to the present course layout. Old Tom Morris was first invited to set out "proper holes" by the secretary John Sutherland who in his 53 years in office also had some input to the design. Donald Ross before he sailed to America to become one of the worlds highly regarded golf course architects was Professional and Head Green Keeper and some holes bear his hallmark. After the war, to replace some holes that had been levelled, George Duncan laid out 5-6 new holes on land purchased from the Duke of Sutherland.\r\n\r\nThis piecemeal approach belies the suggestion that a camel is a horse designed by a committee, but it does not mean that the Club makes a habit of tinkering with the layout. While recognising the need for evolution, the case for any change to the course needs to be made very strongly before anything is touched and those returning even after a period of some years will be comfortable with familiar features.	2011-08-31 15:02:12.044165	2011-09-08 15:48:32.809739	courses		\N	Scotland	Golf at Royal Dornoch, Scotland | Your Golf Tours	Centuries before a golf club was formed at Dornoch, the game of golf was recorded as being played in 1616 on the town lands on the links along the seashore. The Club is proud to play on the third of the first three golf links in Scotland following St Andrews 1552 and Leith 1593.
114	Royal Porthcawl	royal-porthcawl	#Royal Porthcawl\r\n\r\nWhile it is not on the official Open Championship rotation, there are many who believe that Royal Porthcawl is as good as any links course in the United Kingdom, and it leads the pack of quality seaside courses on the South Wales coast. Absolutely unmissable is not an understatement when it comes to your next venture to Wales.\r\n\r\nWith better than 100 years of golfing history under its belt, Royal Porthcawl oozes character and has a rich heritage. For many years, this uncomplicated and unadulterated links course has attracted golfing purists from all over the world.\r\n\r\nCombine Royal Porthcawl with a discovery of other Welsh gems such as Pennard, Southerndown and Pyle & Kenfig, as well as the chance to experience The Celtic Manor Resort and its three courses - led by The Twenty Ten.	2011-08-31 16:31:10.872791	2011-09-08 15:49:41.51244	courses		\N	Wales	Golf at Royal Porthcawl, South Wales | Your Golf Tours	While it is not on the official Open Championship rotation, there are many who believe that Royal Porthcawl is as good as any links course in the United Kingdom, and it leads the pack of quality seaside courses on the South Wales coast.
100	Royal Portrush	royal-portrush	#Royal Portrush\r\n\r\nRoyal Portush is rightly held in extremely high regard, as the only course outside English or Scottish shores to have hosted the Open Championship, and although it is no longer on the rota to stage the event, it remains a fixture in the top 20 of most credible world course rankings.\r\n\r\nThe rugged shores of County Antrim on the north coast of Northern Ireland - just along from the excellent Portsteward - is the main building block for the outstanding Portrush. 1947 saw Harry S. Colt, the esteemed creator of tracks like Wentworth and Sunningdale, and the great man perked the Northern Irish gem up to the standard of today.\r\n\r\nRoyal Portrush is not the longest of championship links, but when the wind blows this is a truly outstanding test that many golfers view as a classic seaside highlight of their golfing pilgrimage to the Emerald Isle.	2011-08-31 16:15:59.450393	2011-09-08 15:49:49.824867	courses		\N	Ireland	Golf at Royal Portrush, Northern Ireland | Your Golf Tours	Royal Portush is rightly held in extremely high regard, as the only course outside English or Scottish shores to have hosted the Open Championship, and although it is no longer on the rota to stage the event, it remains a fixture in the top 20 of most credible world course rankings.
120	San Roque Club	san-roque-club	#San Roque Club\r\n\r\nSan Roque is one of the most prestigious private clubs in Spain, with a rich golfing history and two glorious courses. The club was formerly the regular venue for European Tour final qualifying, and offers a genuine championship experience with superb onsite facilities.\r\n\r\nThe 1997 Ryder Cup, staged at nearby Valderrama, saw the visiting American team choose San Roque and its collection of suites as their base for the week, and there is plenty of memorabilia to document their stay. Follow in their footsteps by enjoying a round at San Roque during your golf tour in Spain.\r\n\r\nSan Roque in fact has two courses - the Old and New - which are difficult to split in terms of quality. The Old has the more illustrious reputation in terms of hosting the final stage of Q School, but the New is an equally impressive layout. Tough from the tee, San Roque will test every facet of your game to the full, and is a glorious place to enjoya day's golf.	2011-08-31 16:39:08.131358	2011-09-08 15:50:29.647187	courses		\N	Spain	Golf at San Roque Club, Spain | Your Golf Tours	San Roque is one of the most prestigious private clubs in Spain, with a rich golfing history and two glorious courses. The club was formerly the regular venue for European Tour final qualifying, and offers a genuine championship experience with superb onsite facilities.
77	Southport & Ainsdale Golf Club	southport-ainsdale-golf-club	#Southport & Ainsdale Golf Club\r\n\r\nSouthport and Ainsdale, or S&A as it is known by locals and members alike, is another unsung hero of Southport and the region that is informally called 'England's Golf Coast'. But it has deep roots, having been designed by the great James Braid and hosted two Ryder Cups.\r\n\r\n1933 and 1937 saw professionals from the United States travel to Southport and Ainsdale to compete with their counterparts from the UK, the site being chosen beacause is really is a classic English links.\r\n\r\nUsed for Open Championship qualifying when the event is staged at nearby Birkdale, S&A ranks highly with lovers of seaside golf, and is an undiluted links that is frequently included in lists of the UK's top 50 courses.\r\n\r\nInclude Southport & Ainsdale in your golf tour itinerary alongside the likes of Birkdale and Hillside and you will have achieve a magnificent understanding of the quality and concentration of the links golf around Southport itself, one of the world's great seaside golf destinations.	2011-08-31 15:42:55.421841	2011-09-08 15:50:40.598669	courses		\N	England	Golf at Southport & Ainsdale Golf Club, England | Your Golf Tours	Southport and Ainsdale, or S&A as it is known by locals and members alike, is another unsung hero of Southport and the region that is informally called 'England's Golf Coast'. But it has deep roots, having been designed by the great James Braid and hosted two Ryder Cups.
32	St Andrews Castle Course	st-andrews-castle-course	#St Andrews Castle Course\r\n\r\nDavid McLay Kidd and his team have transformed featureless farmland into an exciting links-like challenge set above the cliff-tops at Kinkell.\r\n\r\nKidd takes his place among a select group, for the list of course architects who have worked at St Andrews is in itself remarkable.\r\n\r\nThe Castle Course at St Andrews will have an unparalleled pedigree, joining a family of courses that have attracted the very best players in the history of the game as well as untold thousands of golfers eager to experience for themselves the thrill of the ancient links, which were given over to the people of the town in 1123 by King David I of Scotland.\r\n\r\nAlthough the Castle Course is not a links course it has been designed with the Scottish links tradition very much in mind. The approaches to the green will be similar to the greens themselves so that running shots will be playable as well as pitches. Also in the Scottish tradition, the grasses being cultivated at the site are a bent and fescue mix.\r\n\r\nFescues will also feature strongly in the extensive areas of natural rough and wild meadow which will provide a variety of habitats for wildlife including the very rare maiden pink species which has been found on the 220 acre (90 hectare) site. The construction of the Castle Course has been a model development, with full consideration given to environmental factors.\r\n\r\nThe experience of playing the Castle Course will be a treat for the senses. The North Sea is a visible presence on every hole while the view towards St Andrews is one of the finest possible.	2011-08-31 14:24:45.618433	2011-09-08 15:51:08.524933	courses		\N	Scotland	Golf at St Andrews Castle Course, Scotland | Your Golf Tours	The experience of playing the Castle Course will be a treat for the senses. The North Sea is a visible presence on every hole while the view towards St Andrews is one of the finest possible.
30	St Andrews New Course	st-andrews-new-course	#St Andrews New Course\r\n\r\nOpened in April 1895, the course was built in response to increasing demand for golf at St Andrews, both from locals and from the visitors who were flocking to the town in increasing numbers on the recently constructed railway.\r\n\r\nThe construction of the New Course was paid for by the Royal and Ancient Golf Club as part of an arrangement under which the club was allocated the right to certain starting times on the Old Course. These arrangements were enshrined in the first Act of Parliament concerning the Links which was passed in 1894 and was the forerunner of the current Act of 1974 which specifies how the links are to be run.\r\n\r\nThe R&A engaged W Hall Blyth, an Edinburgh civil engineer, to design the New Course, and entrusted the layout to "Old" Tom Morris and his right-hand man David Honeyman.\r\n\r\nThe result is a classic links course which uses the natural features of the land to create a first class golfing challenge. The course has the traditional out and back layout, with the 18th green just to the right of the first tee. It also has, in the great St Andrews tradition, shared fairways and even a double green at the 3rd and 15th holes.\r\n\r\nIt has frequently been said that if the New Course were not situated next to the Old, then its star would have shone with a far greater degree of brilliance.\r\n\r\nLocated as it is in the shadow of its illustrious neighbour, the New Course can be considered one of St Andrews` best kept secrets.	2011-08-31 14:22:58.382115	2011-09-08 15:51:35.895071	courses		\N	Scotland	Golf at St Andrews New Course, Scotland | Your Golf Tours	Opened in April 1895, the course was built in response to increasing demand for golf at St Andrews, both from locals and from the visitors who were flocking to the town in increasing numbers on the recently constructed railway.
21	St Andrews Old Course	st-andrews-old-course	#St Andrews Old Course\r\n\r\n"I fell in love with it the first day I played it. There's just no other golf course that is even remotely close." Jack Nicklaus\r\n\r\n"Without a doubt I like it the best of all the Open venues. It's my favourite course in the world." Tiger Woods\r\n\r\nThe oldest golf course in the world has many remarkable features which help make it so special to golfers around the world.\r\nIt is the Home of Golf where golf was first played 600 years ago and yet it remains a real test of golf for today's champions. Despite its reputation and status, it is a public course and is one of six public courses on St Andrews Links.\r\n\r\nThe Old Course has evolved over time and was not designed by any one architect. The people who played a major role in shaping it are Daw Anderson (1850s), Old Tom Morris (1860s- 1900) and Dr Alister Mackenzie (1930s).\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its particular physical features including 112 bunkers, some of which are especially famous e.g. 'Hell' on the long 14th, 'Strath' on the short 11th and the Road Bunker at what is probably the most famous golf hole in the world, the 17th or Road Hole (so called because a road - which is in play - runs hard against the back edge of the green).\r\n\r\nAnother peculiar feature of the Old Course is the double greens where the outward and inward holes are cut on the same putting surface. These greens are large, not surprisingly, and golfers can be faced with putts of almost 100 yards.\r\n\r\nThe Old Course is also unusual in that it starts and finishes in the town, but its truly remarkable feature is that in today's modern golfing world, a course which has evolved over six centuries, remains a true test of championship golf.\r\n\r\nFor a guaranteed tee time it is recommended to book at least one year in advance of your visit. The other courses follow a similar procedure. The Old Course is also available through the daily ballot or by advance reservation request.\r\n\r\nPlease contact us to secure a coveted tee time reservation.	2011-08-31 14:04:09.9967	2011-09-08 15:51:56.479483	courses		\N	Scotland	Golf at St Andrews Old Course, Scotland | Your Golf Tours	The oldest golf course in the world has many remarkable features which help make it so special to golfers around the world. It is the Home of Golf where golf was first played 600 years ago and yet it remains a real test of golf for today's champions.
88	Strandhill Golf Club	strandhill-golf-club	#Strandhill Golf Club\r\n\r\nStrandhill is one of those unheralded courses that attracts little attention, yet it has a loyal following packed with golfing aficionados who appreciate the chance to experience its superb courses and equally impressive coastal setting.\r\n\r\nDescribe by the great Christie O'Connor as "the jewel of the West", Strandhill is well worth including in your Irish golf tour itinerary, where a warm welcome awaits those willing to head off the beaten track a bit.\r\n\r\nAlthough it feels rugged and isolated, Strandhill has the added bonus of being just five miles from Sligo itself, which makes it easy to access and great for a game whilst based in town.	2011-08-31 16:00:20.613572	2011-09-08 15:52:19.006064	courses		\N	Ireland	Golf at Strandhill Golf Club, Ireland | Your Golf Tours	Strandhill is one of those unheralded courses that attracts little attention, yet it has a loyal following packed with golfing aficionados who appreciate the chance to experience its superb courses and equally impressive coastal setting.
104	Tralee Golf Club	tralee-golf-club	#Tralee Golf Club\r\n\r\nHeading to South West Ireland to play the best courses? Then don't miss out on Tralee, a stunning seaside creation that was mapped out by Arnold Palmer. Arnie famously said of Tralee: "I may have designed the first nine, but surely God designed the back nine."\r\n\r\nThis modern classic was unveiled in 1984, so is now well matured, and it remains as popular as ever. Palmer's links is uncomplicated, merely making use of the inspirational local terrain; each hole is beautifully cut into the towering dunes, creating a collection of distinct holes.\r\n\r\nThe Atlantic washes the Co. Kerry shores on this rugged corner of South West Ireland, all adding up to a truly phenomenal golfing experience, and one that we cannot recommend highly enough.	2011-08-31 16:19:56.699085	2011-09-08 15:53:22.376247	courses		\N	Ireland	Golf at Tralee Golf Club, Ireland | Your Golf Tours	Heading to South West Ireland to play the best courses? Then don't miss out on Tralee, a stunning seaside creation that was mapped out by Arnold Palmer. Arnie famously said of Tralee: "I may have designed the first nine, but surely God designed the back nine."
170	Foxhills Club & Resort	foxhills-club-resort	#Foxhills Club & Resort\r\n\r\nFoxhills, set in leafy Surrey some 30 minutes from the heart of London, is a lovely manor house hotel that provides the ideal luxury starting point for a golf tour around the capital city and its surroundings.\r\n\r\nLooking out over immaculately manicured grounds, the hotel boasts 70 well appointed bedrooms and suites that are ideal for golfers and non-golfers alike. The country club atmosphere will ensure a relaxed environment, while Foxhills has comprehensive facilities both on the course and away from it.\r\n\r\nAfter tackling one of the two tree lined gems at Foxhills, golfers can head to health club, where highlights include indoor and outdoor swimming pools, a gym, sauna, squash and tennis courts, plus the opportunity to enjoy a relaxing spa treatment.\r\n\r\nThe Manor Restaurant, dating back to 1841, is the resort's signature dining room, while the Summerhouse Brasserie is ideal for light snacks and overlooks the outdoor pool. 	2011-09-02 15:40:03.386664	2011-09-08 15:59:30.420243	hotels		\N	England	Foxhills Club & Resort, Surrey, England | Your Golf Tours	Foxhills, set in leafy Surrey some 30 minutes from the heart of London, is a lovely manor house hotel that provides the ideal luxury starting point for a golf tour around the capital city and its surroundings.
191	Marriott Praia D'El Rey Hotel	marriott-praia-del-rey-hotel	#Marriott Praia D'El Rey Hotel\r\n\r\nThe setting at the Marriott Praia D'El Rey Hotel could not be much more appetising; on one side the resort looks out over the outstanding championship golf course, and on the other it looks down over the cliffs to the Atlantic shores. Five star luxury throughout is the hallmark of this international standard resort, with superb facilities, dining and service.\r\n\r\nEvery one of the 197 guest rooms and suites is spacious, and sets the stage for a luxurious portion of your golf tour in Portugal, with amenities including individual climate control, satellite television, and private terraces, many of which look out to the Atlantic.\r\n\r\nExtensive sport and leisure facilities are available for those feeling active, while the spa at Praia d'El Rey is a haven of relaxation. Dining at the resort is a treat, with highlights such as the Romy fine dining restaurant, while the local area is great to explore - head down to the 18th century fishing port Peniche for a charming atmosphere and excellent fish restaurants.	2011-09-02 15:55:40.453806	2011-09-08 16:00:58.628811	hotels		\N	Portugal	Marriott Praia D'El Rey Hotel, Portugal | Your Golf Tours	The setting at the Marriott Praia D'El Rey Hotel could not be much more appetising; on one side the resort looks out over the outstanding championship golf course, and on the other it looks down over the cliffs to the Atlantic shores.
192	Palacio Estoril Hotel	http-yourgolftours-com-palacio-estoril-hotel-asp	#Palacio Estoril Hotel\r\n\r\nThe rich history of the Palacio Estoril tracks back to the 1930s, and the lustre of this opulent hotel has not diminished - the five star establishment is an icon in the sought after coastal retreat of Estoril, and is a luxurious place to base a part of a golf tour in the Lisbon area.\r\n\r\nSpread tastefully across five floors of the striking hotel, the accommodation at the Palacio Estoril comes courtesy of 161 guest rooms, with a high proportion of suites. Make you stay truly special by upgrading to one of these marvellous rooms, which boast period features and beautiful furnishings.\r\n\r\nFrom the grandiose luxury of the hotel, you will be able to explore on foot the delightful marina town of Estoril, long established as an upmarket playground, with its casinos and excellent restaurants. In golfing terms, the Palacio Estoril brings the likes of Oitavos, Praia d'El Rey and Penha Longa within easy reach, all adding up to golf tour packages of the highest order.	2011-09-02 15:56:09.594426	2011-09-08 16:01:21.785327	hotels		\N	Spain	Palacio Estoril Hotel, Spain | Your Golf Tours	The rich history of the Palacio Estoril tracks back to the 1930s, and the lustre of this opulent hotel has not diminished - the five star establishment is an icon in the sought after coastal retreat of Estoril, and is a luxurious place to base a part of a golf tour in the Lisbon area.
200	Saunton Golf Course	saunton-golf-course	Saunton occupies a prestigious position among the elite of links golf in the United Kingdom, with two top class courses and a setting that must be seen to be believed. The East Course is the more senior of the duo, and is consistently ranked in the country's top 100 courses; in fact, many astute observers believe that Saunton has the quality to host the Open Championship.\r\n\r\nThe East Course, designed by Herbert Fowler, is in fact often on the fringes of England's top ten courses, and is set against the irresistable backdrop of the Braunton Burrows sand dunes, which have been marked as a point of environmental interest by UNESCO. Fowler's routing of the monumental East Course reaches around 6,700 yards, which is short by modern championship standards, but the daunting collection of strong par-4s and the near ever-present wind make Saunton's East Course a brute. Not only that, it is one of the very best to include in a golf tour of England's South West.\r\n\r\nWhile the East Course takes most of the plaudits, Saunton's West Course should never be underestimated. Originally opened in the 1930s, the West was subsequently used as an air force training field, and fell into disrepair for some four decades. 1975 saw the esteemed Frank Pennink draw up plans for the course's revival, and it is now a hugely enjoyable and challenging links golf experience.	2011-09-13 10:54:35.077736	2011-09-13 10:58:24.735449	courses		\N	England	Saunton Golf Course, South West Golf Tours - YourGolfTours.com	Saunton occupies a prestigious position among the elite of links golf in the United Kingdom, with two top class courses and a setting that must be seen to be believed. The East Course is the more senior of the duo, and is consistently ranked in the country's top 100 courses; in fact, many astute observers believe that Saunton has the quality to host the Open Championship.
208	Dona Filipa Hotel	dona-filipa-hotel	The Dona Filipa Hotel stands as an icon on the Algarve, having for decades been welcoming golfers to the region and offering outstanding hospitality in a five-star setting. The classic Portuguese style and laid back atmosphere is to be expected at Dona Filipa, which also offers guests the chance to experience the phenomenal San Lorenzo Golf Course, ranked as one of the very best in Europe.\r\n\r\nSitting in the prestigious Vale do Lobo estate, and within 30 minutes of the regional airport at Faro, Dona Filipa has a fantastic setting, just moments from the iconic red cliffs overlooking the sandy shores of the Algarve. Within walking distance of the hotel are a number of bars and restaurants, while the large marina at Vilamoura is a short taxi ride away.\r\n\r\nInside Dona Filipa is a collection of 154 rooms and suites, all spacious and with private terrace or balcony, plus air-conditioning, satellite television and mini-bar. The hotel serves an excellent breakfast and has a sparkling outdoor pool, while the onsite attractions include the San Lorenzo Bar, ideal for a pre-dinner cocktail, and the superb fine dining in the Duarte Grill.	2011-09-13 11:25:23.594213	2011-09-13 11:25:33.327673	hotels		\N	Portugal	Dona Filipa Hotel, Vale do Lobo, Algarve - YourGolfTours.com	The Dona Filipa Hotel stands as an icon on the Algarve, having for decades been welcoming golfers to the region and offering outstanding hospitality in a five-star setting. The classic Portuguese style and laid back atmosphere is to be expected at Dona Filipa, which also offers guests the chance to experience the phenomenal San Lorenzo Golf Course, ranked as one of the very best in Europe.
209	Quinta do Lago Hotel	quinta-do-lago-hotel	Overlooking the Ria Formosa and the Algarve shoreline, the Quinta do Lago Hotel is a beacon of luxury and a high class retreat for golfers staying on Portugal's sun-blushed southern coast. Intimate and private, the Quinta do Lago Hotel is among the best golf hotels in Europe.\r\n\r\nWith just 121 guest rooms and suites, you will enjoy personal and attentive service at Quinta do Lago, which sits at the centre of a phenomenal 2,000 acres of woodland and pines. Custom climate control, satellite television, private terraces and the finest bedding and linen are among the highlights of the guest rooms, which are sure to offer you complete comfort during your golf vacation.\r\n\r\nThe golf surrounding the Quinta do Lago Hotel is renowned, but there are other opportunities to enjoy; the state-of-the-art spa has phenomenal hydrotherapy experiences as well as any number of indulgent treatments, while dining at Quinta do Lago is also to be eagerly anticipated. Brisa do Mar for classic Portuguese flavours and Ca' d'Oro for Italian fine dining are among the highlights.	2011-09-13 11:29:04.10076	2011-09-13 11:29:36.840539	hotels		\N	Portugal	Quinta do Lago Hotel, Algarve Golf Tours - YourGolfTours.com	Overlooking the Ria Formosa and the Algarve shoreline, the Quinta do Lago Hotel is a beacon of luxury and a high class retreat for golfers staying on Portugal's sun-blushed southern coast. Intimate and private, the Quinta do Lago Hotel is among the best golf hotels in Europe.
